          <canvas id="inflationChart"></canvas>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Decade table -->
      <div class="decade-table-section">
        <h2>Historical US Inflation Rates by Decade</h2>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Decade</th>
              <th>Avg. Annual Rate</th>
              <th>Cumulative</th>
              <th>$100 Became</th>
              <th>Key Events</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody id="decade-tbody"></tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- SEO content -->
      <div class="seo-content">
        <h2>How the Inflation Calculator Works</h2>
        <p>Our inflation calculator uses the Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers (CPI-U) published by the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics. The CPI tracks the average change in prices for a basket of consumer goods and services, including food, housing, transportation, medical care, and recreation.</p>
        <p>To calculate how much a past dollar amount is worth today, we divide the current year's CPI by the original year's CPI, then multiply by the dollar amount. This gives you the equivalent purchasing power after accounting for cumulative price changes.</p>

        <h2>Understanding Purchasing Power</h2>
        <p>Purchasing power refers to how much a unit of currency can buy. When inflation rises, each dollar buys less. For example, $1 in 1960 had the same buying power as roughly $10.60 in 2025. This doesn't mean everything got more expensive — some goods got cheaper (electronics, for example) — but on average, the cost of living rose significantly.</p>
        <p>This is why financial planners emphasize thinking in "real" (inflation-adjusted) terms rather than "nominal" (face value) terms when planning for retirement or long-term savings goals.</p>

        <h2>Why Inflation Matters for Your Finances</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Retirement planning:</strong> If you need $50,000/year today, you'll need significantly more in 20–30 years to maintain the same lifestyle.</li>
          <li><strong>Salary negotiations:</strong> A raise that doesn't keep pace with inflation is effectively a pay cut in real terms.</li>
          <li><strong>Investment returns:</strong> An investment returning 6% while inflation is 3% only yields ~3% real growth.</li>
          <li><strong>Debt strategy:</strong> Fixed-rate debt becomes cheaper in real terms as inflation rises, since you repay with less valuable dollars.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Inflation-Beating Strategies</h2>
        <p>Historically, equities (stocks) have outpaced inflation by a wide margin, returning roughly 7% annually after inflation. Other inflation hedges include real estate, Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities (TIPS), I-Bonds, and commodities. Keeping excess cash in a standard savings account often means losing purchasing power over time.</p>
        <p>Use our <a href="/compound-interest-calculator" style="color:var(--accent-color)">compound interest calculator</a> to see how your investments grow in nominal terms, then compare with this inflation calculator to understand your real returns. You can also explore our <a href="/investment-calculator" style="color:var(--accent-color)">investment calculator</a> for more detailed projections.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            What is inflation and how does it affect my money?
            <span class="faq-arrow">&#9660;</span>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Inflation is the rate at which the general level of prices for goods and services rises over time, reducing purchasing power. If inflation averages 3% per year, something that costs $100 today would cost about $103 next year. Over decades, this compounds significantly — $100 in 1990 has the same buying power as roughly $240 today.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            How is the Consumer Price Index (CPI) used to measure inflation?
            <span class="faq-arrow">&#9660;</span>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>The Consumer Price Index (CPI) tracks the average change in prices paid by urban consumers for a basket of goods and services. The Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) publishes CPI data monthly. To calculate inflation between two years, you divide the CPI of the later year by the CPI of the earlier year. Our calculator uses CPI-U (All Urban Consumers) annual averages.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            What is the average US inflation rate?
            <span class="faq-arrow">&#9660;</span>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>The average annual US inflation rate from 1960 to 2025 is approximately 3.7%. However, this varies significantly by decade — the 1970s saw average inflation above 7% due to oil crises, while the 2010s averaged below 2%. Recent years (2021–2023) saw elevated inflation above 4% before moderating.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            How do I protect my savings from inflation?
            <span class="faq-arrow">&#9660;</span>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>To protect against inflation, consider investing in assets that historically outpace inflation: stocks (average ~10% annual return), real estate, Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities (TIPS), and I-Bonds. Keeping all your savings in a standard savings account typically loses purchasing power over time since interest rates often trail inflation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">
            What is the difference between nominal and real returns?
            <span class="faq-arrow">&#9660;</span>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <p>Nominal returns are the raw percentage gain on an investment before accounting for inflation. Real returns subtract the inflation rate to show the actual increase in purchasing power. For example, if your investment earned 8% in a year with 3% inflation, your real return was approximately 5%. Always consider real returns when evaluating long-term investment performance.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </main>
  </div>

  <!-- FAQ schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

  <script is:inline>
    // CPI-U Annual Averages (1960–2025, BLS data)
    const CPI = {
      1960:29.6,1961:29.9,1962:30.2,1963:30.6,1964:31.0,1965:31.5,1966:32.4,1967:33.4,1968:34.8,1969:36.7,
      1970:38.8,1971:40.5,1972:41.8,1973:44.4,1974:49.3,1975:53.8,1976:56.9,1977:60.6,1978:65.2,1979:72.6,
      1980:82.4,1981:90.9,1982:96.5,1983:99.6,1984:103.9,1985:107.6,1986:109.6,1987:113.6,1988:118.3,1989:124.0,
      1990:130.7,1991:136.2,1992:140.3,1993:144.5,1994:148.2,1995:152.4,1996:156.9,1997:160.5,1998:163.0,1999:166.6,
      2000:172.2,2001:177.1,2002:179.9,2003:184.0,2004:188.9,2005:195.3,2006:201.6,2007:207.3,2008:215.3,2009:214.5,
      2010:218.1,2011:224.9,2012:229.6,2013:233.0,2014:236.7,2015:237.0,2016:240.0,2017:245.1,2018:251.1,2019:255.7,
      2020:258.8,2021:271.0,2022:292.7,2023:304.7,2024:313.5,2025:319.2
    };

    const CPI_YEARS = Object.keys(CPI).map(Number).sort((a,b) => a - b);
    const LATEST_YEAR = CPI_YEARS[CPI_YEARS.length - 1];

    // Format helpers
    const fmt = (v) => new Intl.NumberFormat('en-US', { style:'currency', currency:'USD', maximumFractionDigits:2 }).format(v);
    const fmtPct = (v) => (v >= 0 ? '+' : '') + v.toFixed(2) + '%';

    // Copy
    window.copyVal = async (id, btn) => {
      try {
        await navigator.clipboard.writeText(document.getElementById(id).innerText);
        const orig = btn.innerText;
        btn.innerText = 'Copied!';
        setTimeout(() => btn.innerText = orig, 2000);
      } catch(e) {}
    };

    // Populate year dropdown
    const yearSelect = document.getElementById('hist-year');
    for (let y = LATEST_YEAR - 1; y >= CPI_YEARS[0]; y--) {
      const opt = document.createElement('option');
      opt.value = y;
      opt.textContent = y;
      if (y === 1990) opt.selected = true;
      yearSelect.appendChild(opt);
    }

    // Mode switching
    const tabs = document.querySelectorAll('.mode-tab');
    tabs.forEach(tab => {
      tab.addEventListener('click', () => {
        tabs.forEach(t => t.classList.remove('active'));
        tab.classList.add('active');
        document.querySelectorAll('.mode-panel').forEach(p => p.classList.remove('active'));
        document.getElementById('panel-' + tab.dataset.mode).classList.add('active');
        calculate();
      });
    });

    // Chart
    const canvas = document.getElementById('inflationChart');
    const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

    function drawChart(labels, values, lineLabel, color) {
      const dpr = window.devicePixelRatio || 1;
      const rect = canvas.parentElement.getBoundingClientRect();
      canvas.width = rect.width * dpr;
      canvas.height = rect.height * dpr;
      ctx.setTransform(1,0,0,1,0,0);
      ctx.scale(dpr, dpr);
      const w = rect.width, h = rect.height;
      ctx.clearRect(0,0,w,h);

      const pad = { top:20, right:20, bottom:40, left:80 };
      const cw = w - pad.left - pad.right;
      const ch = h - pad.top - pad.bottom;

      const maxVal = Math.max(...values);
      const minVal = Math.min(...values);
      const range = maxVal - minVal || 1;

      // Grid
      ctx.strokeStyle = '#2a2010';
      ctx.lineWidth = 1;
      ctx.font = '12px Inter, sans-serif';
      ctx.fillStyle = '#888';
      ctx.textAlign = 'right';
      ctx.textBaseline = 'middle';

      const yTicks = 5;
      for (let i = 0; i <= yTicks; i++) {
        const val = minVal + range * (i / yTicks);
        const y = h - pad.bottom - (ch * (i / yTicks));
        ctx.beginPath();
        ctx.moveTo(pad.left, y);
        ctx.lineTo(w - pad.right, y);
        ctx.stroke();
        let lbl = val >= 1000000 ? '$'+(val/1e6).toFixed(1)+'M' :
                  val >= 1000 ? '$'+(val/1000).toFixed(0)+'k' : '$'+val.toFixed(0);
        ctx.fillText(lbl, pad.left - 10, y);
      }

      // X-axis
      ctx.textAlign = 'center';
      ctx.textBaseline = 'top';
      const xTicks = Math.min(labels.length - 1, 10);
      for (let i = 0; i <= xTicks; i++) {
        const idx = Math.round((labels.length - 1) * i / xTicks);
        const x = pad.left + (cw * idx / (labels.length - 1));
        ctx.beginPath();
        ctx.moveTo(x, h - pad.bottom);
        ctx.lineTo(x, h - pad.bottom + 5);
        ctx.stroke();
        ctx.fillText(labels[idx], x, h - pad.bottom + 10);
      }

      // Line
      ctx.beginPath();
      ctx.strokeStyle = color;
      ctx.lineWidth = 3;
      ctx.lineJoin = 'round';
      values.forEach((val, i) => {
        const x = pad.left + (cw * i / (labels.length - 1));
        const y = h - pad.bottom - (ch * ((val - minVal) / range));
        if (i === 0) ctx.moveTo(x, y); else ctx.lineTo(x, y);
      });
      ctx.stroke();

      // Fill
      const lastX = pad.left + cw;
      ctx.lineTo(lastX, h - pad.bottom);
      ctx.lineTo(pad.left, h - pad.bottom);
      ctx.closePath();
      const r = parseInt(color.slice(1,3),16), g = parseInt(color.slice(3,5),16), b = parseInt(color.slice(5,7),16);
      const grad = ctx.createLinearGradient(0, pad.top, 0, h - pad.bottom);
      grad.addColorStop(0, `rgba(${r},${g},${b},0.2)`);
      grad.addColorStop(1, `rgba(${r},${g},${b},0)`);
      ctx.fillStyle = grad;
      ctx.fill();
    }

    function calculate() {
      const mode = document.querySelector('.mode-tab.active').dataset.mode;

      if (mode === 'historical') {
        const amount = parseFloat(document.getElementById('hist-amount').value) || 0;
        const year = parseInt(document.getElementById('hist-year').value);
        const cpiThen = CPI[year];
        const cpiNow = CPI[LATEST_YEAR];
        const ratio = cpiNow / cpiThen;
        const adjusted = amount * ratio;
        const cumulative = ((ratio - 1) * 100);
        const years = LATEST_YEAR - year;
        const avgAnnual = years > 0 ? (Math.pow(ratio, 1/years) - 1) * 100 : 0;

        document.getElementById('hist-result').innerText = fmt(adjusted);
        document.getElementById('hist-cumulative').innerText = fmtPct(cumulative);
        document.getElementById('hist-annual').innerText = fmtPct(avgAnnual);

        // Chart: purchasing power of the amount from year to now
        const labels = [];
        const values = [];
        for (let y = year; y <= LATEST_YEAR; y++) {
          if (CPI[y] !== undefined) {
            labels.push(String(y));
            values.push(amount * (CPI[y] / cpiThen));
          }
        }
        document.getElementById('chart-subtitle').innerText = `${fmt(amount)} from ${year} adjusted for inflation each year`;
        drawChart(labels, values, 'Value', '#D4A017');

      } else {
        const amount = parseFloat(document.getElementById('fut-amount').value) || 0;
        const years = parseInt(document.getElementById('fut-years').value) || 1;
        const rate = parseFloat(document.getElementById('fut-rate').value) || 0;

        const factor = Math.pow(1 + rate / 100, years);
        const futureValue = amount / factor;
        const needed = amount * factor;
        const cumulative = (factor - 1) * 100;

        document.getElementById('fut-result').innerText = fmt(futureValue);
        document.getElementById('fut-needed').innerText = fmt(needed);
        document.getElementById('fut-cumulative').innerText = fmtPct(cumulative);

        // Update the "You'd need" label
        document.querySelector('#panel-future .result-item:nth-child(2) .result-label').innerText =
          `You'd need this much to equal ${fmt(amount)} today`;

        // Chart: purchasing power declining
        const labels = [];
        const values = [];
        for (let y = 0; y <= years; y++) {
          labels.push('Yr ' + y);
          values.push(amount / Math.pow(1 + rate / 100, y));
        }
        document.getElementById('chart-subtitle').innerText = `How ${fmt(amount)} loses purchasing power at ${rate}% annual inflation`;
        drawChart(labels, values, 'Purchasing Power', '#4A90E2');
      }
    }

    // Decade table
    function buildDecadeTable() {
      const decades = [
        { label:'1960s', start:1960, end:1969, events:'Vietnam War spending, Great Society programs' },
        { label:'1970s', start:1970, end:1979, events:'Oil crises, stagflation, gold standard end' },
        { label:'1980s', start:1980, end:1989, events:'Volcker rate hikes, disinflation' },
        { label:'1990s', start:1990, end:1999, events:'Tech boom, stable growth, low inflation' },
        { label:'2000s', start:2000, end:2009, events:'Dot-com bust, housing bubble, 2008 crisis' },
        { label:'2010s', start:2010, end:2019, events:'Slow recovery, low rates, below-target CPI' },
        { label:'2020s', start:2020, end:2025, events:'COVID stimulus, supply chain shock, rate hikes' },
      ];
      const tbody = document.getElementById('decade-tbody');
      decades.forEach(d => {
        const startCPI = CPI[d.start];
        const endCPI = CPI[d.end];
        const yrs = d.end - d.start;
        const cum = ((endCPI / startCPI) - 1) * 100;
        const avg = (Math.pow(endCPI / startCPI, 1 / yrs) - 1) * 100;
        const became = 100 * (endCPI / startCPI);
        const cls = avg > 5 ? 'high' : avg < 2 ? 'negative' : '';
        const tr = document.createElement('tr');
        tr.innerHTML = `<td>${d.label}</td><td class="${cls}">${avg.toFixed(1)}%</td><td>${cum.toFixed(1)}%</td><td>$${became.toFixed(0)}</td><td style="font-family:var(--font-ui);color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:0.8rem">${d.events}</td>`;
        tbody.appendChild(tr);
      });
    }

    // FAQ toggles
    document.querySelectorAll('.faq-question').forEach(btn => {
      btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const item = btn.parentElement;
        item.classList.toggle('open');
      });
    });

    // Event listeners
    document.querySelectorAll('input[type="number"], select').forEach(el => {
      el.addEventListener('input', calculate);
      el.addEventListener('change', calculate);
    });
    window.addEventListener('resize', calculate);

    buildDecadeTable();
    setTimeout(calculate, 0);
  </script>

  <!-- Related tools -->
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-5 pt-8 pb-12">
    <div class="border-t border-[var(--border-color)] pt-8">
      <p class="text-xs font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] tracking-wide uppercase mb-3">Related Calculators</p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
        <a href="/compound-interest-calculator" class="block bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-5 hover:border-[var(--accent-color)] hover:-translate-y-0.5 transition-all">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-white">Compound Interest Calculator</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] mt-1">See how your investments grow →</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/investment-calculator" class="block bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-5 hover:border-[var(--accent-color)] hover:-translate-y-0.5 transition-all">
          <h3 class="text-base font-bold text-white">Investment Calculator</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] mt-1">Plan your portfolio returns →</p>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</SiteLayout>
